---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import HeroText from '~/components/widgets/HeroText.astro';
import Content from '~/components/widgets/Content.astro';
import Image from '~/components/common/Image.astro';
import { Icon } from 'astro-icon/components';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Bio',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <!-- HeroText Widget ******************* -->
  <HeroText title="Biography" tagline="North Sea Echoes" />

  <!-- Band Profiles Widget ******************* -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 mb-12">
    <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-12 sm:gap-16 justify-center">
      <!-- Ray Alder -->
      <div class="flex flex-col items-center text-center group">
        <div
          class="relative w-48 h-48 sm:w-56 sm:h-56 rounded-full overflow-hidden shadow-lg border-4 border-stone-200 dark:border-stone-800 transition-transform duration-300 group-hover:scale-105"
        >
          <Image
            src="~/assets/images/ray_2024_01_300x300rev.png"
            alt="Ray Alder"
            class="object-cover w-full h-full"
            width={300}
            height={300}
          />
        </div>
        <h3 class="mt-6 text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight dark:text-white font-heading">Ray Alder</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-600 dark:text-slate-400 text-sm mt-1">Vocals</p>
        <div class="w-12 h-0.5 bg-secondary dark:bg-accent my-3"></div>
        <div class="flex space-x-4 mt-2">
          <a
            href="https://twitter.com/realrayalder"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="text-stone-500 hover:text-primary dark:text-stone-400 dark:hover:text-accent transition-colors"
            aria-label="Ray Alder X (Twitter)"
          >
            <Icon name="tabler:brand-x" class="w-6 h-6" />
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://www.facebook.com/RayAlderOfficial"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="text-stone-500 hover:text-primary dark:text-stone-400 dark:hover:text-accent transition-colors"
            aria-label="Ray Alder Facebook"
          >
            <Icon name="tabler:brand-facebook" class="w-6 h-6" />
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://www.instagram.com/rayalderofficial/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="text-stone-500 hover:text-primary dark:text-stone-400 dark:hover:text-accent transition-colors"
            aria-label="Ray Alder Instagram"
          >
            <Icon name="tabler:brand-instagram" class="w-6 h-6" />
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Jim Matheos -->
      <div class="flex flex-col items-center text-center group">
        <div
          class="relative w-48 h-48 sm:w-56 sm:h-56 rounded-full overflow-hidden shadow-lg border-4 border-stone-200 dark:border-stone-800 transition-transform duration-300 group-hover:scale-105"
        >
          <Image
            src="~/assets/images/jim_2024_01_300x300rev.png"
            alt="Jim Matheos"
            class="object-cover w-full h-full"
            width={300}
            height={300}
          />
        </div>
        <h3 class="mt-6 text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight dark:text-white font-heading">Jim Matheos</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-600 dark:text-slate-400 text-sm mt-1">Guitar / Programming</p>
        <div class="w-12 h-0.5 bg-secondary dark:bg-accent my-3"></div>
        <div class="flex space-x-4 mt-2">
          <a
            href="https://www.facebook.com/JimMatheosOfficial"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="text-stone-500 hover:text-primary dark:text-stone-400 dark:hover:text-accent transition-colors"
            aria-label="Jim Matheos Facebook"
          >
            <Icon name="tabler:brand-facebook" class="w-6 h-6" />
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://jimmatheos.com/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="text-stone-500 hover:text-primary dark:text-stone-400 dark:hover:text-accent transition-colors"
            aria-label="Jim Matheos Website"
          >
            <Icon name="tabler:world" class="w-6 h-6" />
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Content Widget: How to Cast a Shadow (2026) ****************** -->
  <Content
    isAfterContent
    isBeforeContent
    isReversed={true}
    image={{
      src: '~/assets/images/NSE_2026_01.jpg',
      alt: 'North Sea Echoes (2026)',
      caption: 'Photo by Jeremy Saffer',
      captionJustification: 'right',
    }}
  >
    <Fragment slot="content">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight dark:text-white sm:text-4xl mb-4 font-heading">
        How to Cast a Shadow (2026)
      </h2>
      <div class="mb-6 font-semibold dark:text-slate-200">
        <p>Ray Alder: Vocals</p>
        <p>Jim Matheos: Guitar / Programming</p>
      </div>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-justify">
        <p>
          On <strong>North Sea Echoes</strong> critically acclaimed 2024 debut, singer Ray Alder and guitarist Jim Matheos
          garnered raves for songs that possess <em
            >"liberating sonic space and emotional vulnerability… from somnambulant electro-fog to gritty, overdriven
            disquiet, to the quietly devastating."</em
          > (<strong>Blabbermouth</strong>)
        </p>
        <p>
          With 2026's <em><strong>How to Cast a Shadow</strong></em>, North Sea Echoes' identity is further explored and
          expanded. Matheos explains, <em
            >"this record is a bit heavier, with several more songs featuring real drums, played by Dennis Leeflang. It
            wasn't necessarily intentional or planned, just the way things shaped up and how they emerged this time."</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          Alder concurs. <em
            >"'I'll Leave a Light On' is much heavier than anything on Really Good Terrible Things, the first NSE album.
            It has a darker melancholic feel that fits well on this album. I loosely based the lyrics on a character
            from my favorite sci-fi series. I won't say which, but they do use the quote 'out there in the black.'"</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          From the radio-ready rock of <em>"All That Comes After"</em> to intimate, escalating <em
            >"A Time of Innocence and Purpose"</em
          > to the powerful, timeless ballad <em>"Villains or Saints,"</em>
          <strong>How to Cast a Shadow</strong> cohesively crosses genres and challenges aural preconceptions.
        </p>
        <p>
          The music that became the title track inspired lyricist Alder. <em
            >"When Ray sent his ideas for this one, it immediately stood out for me as a title track,"</em
          > Matheos says. <em
            >"A combination of title/lyrics/ imagery, and the song itself being a bit longer and having a lot of the
            elements of what NSE sounds like made it a natural choice for me."</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>North Sea Echoes</strong> have been praised for Matheos and Adler <em
            >"maintaining their distinctive identity throughout, neither relying on proven past endeavors nor abandoning
            them completely."</em
          > Indeed, the band and <strong>How to Cast a Shadow</strong> use the duo's shared and separate histories to forge
          a fresh creative opus. Their credits are the stuff of metal legend: Alder has been the vocalist and main co-writer
          for prog metal heroes <strong>Fates Warning</strong> for 37 years, recording 10 albums between 1988 (<em
            ><strong>No Exit</strong></em
          >) and 2020 (<em><strong>Long Day Good Night</strong></em>). Rounding out his discography are seven albums
          with <strong>Redemption</strong>, two solo records, and the band <strong>A-Z</strong>, which debuted in 2022.
        </p>
        <p>
          Revered guitar/producer Matheos is a co-founder of <strong>Fates Warning</strong>, the lineup debuting with
          1984's <em><strong>Night on Bröcken</strong></em> on Metal Blade. In addition to 13 albums with <strong
            >Fates</strong
          >, Matheos launched several solo albums, four LPs alongside former <strong>Dream Theater</strong> keyboardist Kevin
          Moore under the name <strong>OSI</strong>, and <strong>Kings of Mercia</strong>, who launched in 2022.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the last couple years, the ever-prolific Matheos wrote a bunch of material-about 25 songs-track that could
          perhaps wind up in any one of his musical endeavors. The guitarist and singer were ready to work on what would
          become the second <strong>North Sea Echoes</strong> album, and <em
            >"I started sending Ray batches of this material, and he picked ones he wants to work on,"</em
          > Matheos says.
        </p>
        <p>
          Other standout tracks include <em>"Enjoy the View."</em>
          <em>"The guitars and drums have this great drive that builds throughout the song."</em> Alder says. <em
            >"The combination of quiet verses and heavy choruses made me think (lyrically) of a darker side to some
            people. Those who would choose numbness over pain."</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>"Villains Or Saints"</em> is another band favorite, and <strong>NSE</strong> also feels fortunate that they
          found the perfect artwork to complement <em><strong>How to Cast a Shadow</strong></em>. Lauded British
          painter-turned-photographer Chris Friel contributed the cover art. Matheos has worked with Friel in the past (<strong
            >Arch/Matheos</strong
          >, <strong>Tuesday the Sky</strong>) and while these particular images were initially intended for a previous <strong
            >Tuesday the Sky</strong
          > record, <em
            >"when we decided the title for this one we realized those images fit perfectly on How to Cast a Shadow,"</em
          > Matheos explains.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reflecting on <strong>North Sea Echoes</strong>' sophomore album, the duo says, <em
            >"I guess you could say that there are elements of everything we do or have done on this album, yet Fates
            and our various other projects are totally different types of music."</em
          > If <em><strong>Really Good Terrible Things</strong></em> kickstarted <strong>NSE</strong>'s career with <em
            >"hovering subtleties, introspective thoughtful reflections"</em
          > and lyrics with <em>"wisdom and authenticity,"</em>
          <em><strong>How to Cast a Shadow</strong></em> ups the promise of its predecessor. Provocative words of hope, sorrow
          and consciousness are paired with Matheos' equally emotive, varied and deeply moving guitar work.
        </p>
        <p>
          As Alder sings on <em>"All Fall Away,"</em>
          <em
            >"Days blurring into days while bridges turn to rust, nothing flows beneath just stone and dust / And those
            times we feel more lost than found, more let go than held are the moments we become ourselves."</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >"Let it all fall away let it all turn to gray / Give back that borrowed time and take off that mask / Then
            turn to face the path ahead."</em
          >
        </p>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
  </Content>

  <!-- Content Widget: Really Good Terrible Things (2024) ****************** -->
  <Content
    isAfterContent
    isBeforeContent
    isReversed={false}
    image={{
      src: '~/assets/images/NSE_2024_01.jpg',
      alt: 'Jim Matheos and Ray Alder (2024)',
      caption: 'Photo by Jeremy Saffer',
      captionJustification: 'right',
    }}
  >
    <Fragment slot="content">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight dark:text-white sm:text-4xl mb-4 font-heading">
        Really Good Terrible Things (2024)
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-6 text-justify">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold tracking-tight dark:text-white mb-2 font-heading uppercase text-secondary">
            History
          </h3>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400">
            <strong>Ray Alder</strong> and <strong>Jim Matheos</strong>’ musical legacy is vast and lauded, both as
            collaborators and individuals. Alder has been the vocalist and main co-writer for prog metal heroes <strong
              >Fates Warning</strong
            > for the past 35 years. With them he has recorded 10 albums between <em><strong>1988 (No Exit)</strong></em
            > and <em><strong>2020 (Long Day Good Night)</strong></em>. Further rounding out his discography are seven
            albums with Redemption, two solo albums, and the band A-Z with Mark Zonder, which debuted in 2022.
          </p>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400 mt-2">
            Prolific and pioneering guitarist/producer <strong>Matheos</strong> is a co-founder of <strong
              >Fates Warning</strong
            >, the lineup debuting with <em><strong>1984’s Night on Bröcken</strong></em> on Metal Blade. In addition to 13
            albums with Fates, <strong>Matheos</strong>’ myriad other work includes several solo albums, four albums
            alongside former Dream Theater keyboardist Kevin Moore, under the name OSI, and new band, Kings of Mercia, a
            lineup that’s been termed “a hybrid; it’s heavy, but not metal.”
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold tracking-tight dark:text-white mb-2 font-heading uppercase text-secondary">
            North Sea Echoes
          </h3>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400">
            On <strong>North Sea Echoes</strong>’ debut album, <em><strong>Really Good Terrible Things</strong></em>,
            the duo embark upon a fresh musical journey, a new chapter of intimate, moody, and evocative songs
            highlighted by the singles <em>“Open Book,” “Empty,” “Throwing Stones.”</em>
          </p>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400 mt-2">
            <em
              >“Throughout <strong>Really Good Terrible Things</strong>, <strong>Matheos</strong> and <strong
                >Alder</strong
              > serve up the kind of seductive melancholy Fates Warning fans will recognize,”</em
            > says Jeff Wagner, author of the Fates Warning book Destination Onward. <em
              >“Yet there's a thoroughly different approach here: vocals are delivered with a sort of nostalgic sadness,
              and the guitar work is layered in such a way as to feel dreamlike. These are rich sonic landscapes,
              visiting places haunting, beautiful, spectral and secret. The Matheos/Alder partnership is taken to some
              new and wonderful places here,”</em
            > Wagner concludes.
          </p>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400 mt-2">
            <strong>Matheos</strong> and <strong>Alder</strong> began talking about working together again as soon as they
            completed <strong>Fates Warning</strong>’s <em><strong>Long Day Good Night</strong></em>. <em
              >“We just didn’t know what, when, where,”</em
            > says <strong>Matheos</strong>. <em
              >“I had begun work on another Tuesday the Sky record, which is an ambient, mostly instrumental, pet
              project of mine. But the first songs I’d come up with felt like they were more set up for vocals. Ray and
              I had done something similar on Long Days Good Night, a song called ‘When Winter Falls,’ and we both
              really liked the outcome. So I asked him if he’d be onto doing a whole record with a similar approach.”</em
            >
          </p>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400 mt-2">
            The resultant <strong>Really Good Terrible Things</strong> was produced by Matheos with cover art from Simon Ward
            (Kings of Mercia, Marillion). <em><strong>“Open Book”</strong></em> kicks off the record, and was also the first
            song written. <strong>Matheos</strong> felt that <em
              >“with Ray’s lyrics about ending and beginnings, it felt like a good mood to start off with.”</em
            >
            <strong>Alder</strong> adds: <em
              >“The line ‘we’re a cloud behind the moon’ is referring to the fact that we are all basically an
              impossibility. Yet here we are. And we will go on until we can’t. I’m speaking of inevitability.”</em
            >
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold tracking-tight dark:text-white mb-2 font-heading uppercase text-secondary">
            Really Good Terrible Things
          </h3>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400">
            The ominous-sounding <em><strong>“Empty”</strong></em> begins with <strong>Matheos</strong>’ atmospheric
            guitar work and features a powerful drum performance by Gunnar Olsen (Puscifer). <em
              ><strong>“Throwing Stones”</strong></em
            >, also with Olsen on drums, sees the pair tapping their vast influences to create one of the most immediate
            tracks on the record. Lyrically it’s about something called <em>“Cherophobia,”</em> as <strong>Alder</strong
            > explains: <em
              >“Some people have a fear of happiness. They feel that something painful always follows pleasure. So
              they’re sort of locked into this world where they try to feel nothing, and that’s what Cherophobia is, and
              what inspired the lyrics.”</em
            >
          </p>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400 mt-2">
            One of <strong>Matheos</strong>’ favorite tracks is <em><strong>“No Maps”</strong></em>. <strong
              >Matheos</strong
            > had a concept for the lyrics, and <strong>Alder</strong> took it from there: <em
              >“The track was much, much different than what ended up on the album. On the demo there was the sound of a
              freight train quietly moving down the tracks throughout the entire song, along with acoustic guitars. Jim
              said it reminded him of hobos. So I thought I’d write about a wanderer who is happiest being alone. Kind
              of romantic to me, in a weird way.”</em
            >
          </p>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400 mt-2">
            The songwriting process was as familiar one for the Fates Warning vets: <strong>Matheos</strong> demos music,
            then passes it along to <strong>Alder</strong>. <em
              >“If he likes the song, he’ll start coming up with lyrics and melodies. After that, the song will tend go
              through further changes, sometimes minor, sometimes major, as the final form starts to take shape,”</em
            > explains <strong>Matheos</strong>.
          </p>
          <p class="text-muted dark:text-slate-400 mt-2">
            <strong>Really Good Terrible Things</strong> shows the breadth and versatility of the acclaimed pair, along with
            a freshness that belies their long musical partnership. <em
              >“We both still love making music and we really enjoy working together. There’s a good amount of chemistry
              there, I think,”</em
            >
            <strong>Matheos</strong> concludes. <em>“We both know what to expect from each other.”</em>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Fragment>
  </Content>
</Layout>
